# GDScript Style

Godot 4.x, GDScript only. No C#. No GDExtension unless explicitly requested.

## Naming

| Kind      | Convention  | Example              |
| --------- | ----------- | -------------------- |
| Classes   | PascalCase  | `EnemySpawner`       |
| Variables | snake_case  | `current_health`     |
| Functions | snake_case  | `apply_damage()`     |
| Signals   | snake_case  | `enemy_died`         |
| Constants | UPPER_CASE  | `MAX_HEALTH`         |
| Scenes    | PascalCase  | `Player.tscn`        |
| Folders   | snake_case  | `enemy_manager/`     |

## Code Style

- Write clean, explicit code. Avoid clever solutions.
- Keep functions short. Keep files organized.
- Avoid deeply nested code and duplicated logic.
- Prefer explicit code over hidden magic.
- Every public class begins with a short description comment.
- Comments explain WHY, not WHAT. Avoid narrating obvious code.

## Performance Guardrails

Assume the game may have thousands of enemies, thousands of projectiles, and hundreds of pickups.

- Do not allocate objects every frame.
- Avoid unnecessary work in `_process()` and `_physics_process()`.
- Prefer event-driven code (signals, callbacks) over polling.
- Pool projectiles, enemies, and other frequently spawned nodes.
- Optimize only when necessary, but avoid obviously inefficient code.

## Error Handling

- Never silently ignore errors.
- Print meaningful warnings via `push_warning()` / `push_error()`.
- Validate inputs on public functions.
- Avoid crashes.
